## When to use this component

Use this component when you need to show a list of information, such as search results, across multiple pages.

You might do this when:
- showing the full list on a single page makes the page too long to load
- the results further down the list are not needed by most users

## When not to use this component

Only break up lists into pages if it improves the performance or usability of your service.

Do not use this component to link sections together as a multi-page article.
Instead, use links named after the title of each section. Also, [see the Step by Step navigation pattern](/patterns/step-by-step-navigation/).

Avoid using the 'infinite scroll' technique to automatically load content when the user approaches the bottom of the page. This causes problems for keyboard users.

## How it works

Add the pagination component after the main content of each page in the list of
results.

[View an example of the component in a standard GOV.UK page template](in-page/index.html).

Show the page number to the title of the page so the user can see it in browser tabs and bookmarks. For example 'Search results (page 1 of 4)'.

Do not show pagination if there's only one page of results.

Redirect users to the first page if they enter a URL with a page number that does not exist.

### Previous and next links

Previous and next links should be labelled 'Previous page' and 'Next page'.

{{ example({group: "components", item: "pagination", example: "default", html: true, nunjucks: true, open: false, size: "s"}) }}

If horizontal space is limited you can visually hide the word 'page'.

{{ example({group: "components", item: "pagination", example: "compact-links", html: true, nunjucks: true, open: false, size: "s"}) }}

Do not show the previous page link on the first page — and do not show the next page link on the last page.

{{ example({group: "components", item: "pagination", example: "first-page", html: true, nunjucks: true, open: false, size: "s"}) }}

